It was announced Thursday that Kazuo Ishiguro won the Booker Prize for his novel "The  Remains of The Day".
The prize is worth 32,000 dollars.
The winning novel is a love  story about a butler's English vacation that explores the provoking themes of class,  tradition and duty.
Ishiguro was born in Japan, and came to England at the age of six He lives in London.
He  was a Booker finalist in 1986.
In accepting the award, Ishiguro paid tribute to Salman  Rushdie, the 1988 runner-up for the Booker, who is now in hiding. 
